         <listPerson>
            <person xml:id="pers1292">
               <p>A native of <placeName>Exeter</placeName>, Ley was active as a Methodist preacher
                     <date from="1758" to="1763">1758–63</date>, though his name never appears in
                  the Minutes. This was likely because of Ley&apos;s intention to seek ordination.
                  He matriculated St. Edmund Hall, <placeName>Oxford</placeName> in <date
                     when="1764-04">April 1764</date>, completing his studies the following year. He
                  was ordained deacon in <date when="1765-10">Oct. 1765</date> and took a curacy in
                     <placeName>Lakenheath (Suffolk</placeName>). In <date when="1769">1769</date>
                  he was ordained priest, and appointed vicar of <placeName>East
                     Tilsbury</placeName>, a position he held until his death. He continued to
                  support the Wesley brothers through the early <date>1770s</date>.</p>
            </person>
         </listPerson>
      </body>
